Additional Information:
In the context of ISA2 this "customization" is also known as "Application Profile".
An identifier for this document, assigned by the sender.

Free-form text pertinent to this document, conveying information that is not contained explicitly in other structures.

Identifies an instance of executing a profile, to associate all transactions in a collaboration.
Additional Information:
In RPaM, the transactions are defined in the Use Case and Scenarios documented. Each Use Case Scenario represents one transaction in a collaboration that encompasses the exchange of several documents, at least the exchange of one eMandateRequest and eMandateResponses.
Pattern proposed for the identification of the Transactions in RPaM: abbreviations of "Transaction Use Case nn Scenario" nn, separated with "-". Examples:
T-UC01-S01 T-UC01-S02 T-UC01-S03 etc.
Bweare that in RPaM only two Cross-border Interoperability Use Cases were identified (UC-0 and UC-1). UC-0 was considered part of the current eIDAS transactional environment, and therefore out of the scope of the RPaM Ontology.
Please refer to the RPaM documentations for more details.

Identifies a user-defined application profile of RPaM being used.
Additional Information: Application Profile (AP) is used herein as in ISA2, meaning a customisation of the standard for its use in the context of the European Union. If no RPaM-AP identifier is indicated in the eMandateRequest document then the standard RPaM is the default model being used.

The identifier of the eMandate Request document that triggered this eMandate Response document.
Additional Information: To completely identify with no ambiguities a document at least two data are mandatory: its identifier and its content version identifier.
The version of the RPaM specification upon which this document instance is based on.

The system that issued the eMandateRequest document.
Additional Information: 1. The system belongs to an rpam:Agent (a person or an organisation). 2. Beware that this system may not be the System that created the eMandate Registry, but the one that issued it. 3. The rpam:Agent that owns the rpam:System can be contacted (rpam:Contact) to identify the rest of actors behind the transaction.

Information Requirement and Constraint. Additional information: A Criterion with two Properties:  
  1. An Information Requirement;
  2. A constrain applied to this Information Requirement.
This can be used for requirements that are very specific to the SP service. For example, the EFSA (European Food Safety Authority), requires that the eMandate Response specify in the response whether the mandatee(s) has ever breached one specific regulation related to food safety (self-declaration of responsibility). Information Requirement (IR): The mandatee is not in breach of any of the articles of the regulation...". Constraint: "Regulation 1924/2006 on nutrition and health claims made on foods" (http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/ALL/?uri=CELEX:02006R1924-20121129).
